    "duplicate_of": null,
    "body": "<h1>Your Gujarati Customers Know When You're Reading From a Translated Script</h1>\n<h2>Let Me Tell You a Story</h2>\n<p>Let me tell you about Rajesh. He runs an insurance agency in Coimbatore. His customers speak Tamil at home, English at the office, and a fluid mix of both when discussing premiums and policy details.</p>\n<p>Rajesh tried one of those 'multilingual' voice platforms. The demo looked great. But when his customer said 'Enaku ₹5 lakh coverage venum, but EMI ethana varum?' — the system froze.</p>\n<p>Why? Because it was trained on textbook Tamil and textbook English. Not the Tamil-English that 80 million Indians actually speak every day.</p>\n<p>Code-switching isn't a bug in Indian speech. It's the feature. And most voice platforms treat it like an afterthought.</p>\n<h2>The Problem Nobody Talks About</h2>\n<p>My uncle runs a pharmacy in Bengaluru. His customers speak Kannada at home, English at work, and a beautiful mix of both at his shop. No translation app captures that. No textbook teaches it.</p>\n<p>Yet every 'multilingual' voice platform claims they 'support' Kannada.</p>\n<h2>How Language Understanding Actually Works</h2>\n<p>Most people think voice AI 'speaks' languages. That's only half true. The real magic is in <strong>understanding</strong> — and understanding Indian speech is genuinely hard.</p>\n<p>Here's why:</p>\n<p><strong>Indian speech isn't 'pure' language.</strong> A customer might say: 'Mujhe ₹5 lakh ka loan chahiye, EMI kitna hoga 3 years ke liye?' That's Hindi + English in one sentence. A 'multilingual' system that switches languages sentence-by-sentence can't handle this. It needs to understand both simultaneously.</p>\n<p><strong>Regional accents vary massively.</strong> Chennai Tamil isn't Madurai Tamil. Mumbai Hindi isn't Lucknow Hindi. A system trained on one accent fails on the other.</p>\n<p><strong>Speakers don't follow scripts.</strong> Your customer might interrupt, change topics, ask unexpected questions, or go silent while thinking. The AI needs to handle all of this naturally.</p>\n<p><strong>What Speaksy does differently:</strong> It's trained on real Indian phone conversations — not textbook language, not translated scripts. It understands Hinglish, Tanglish, Tenglish, Kanglish, Marathi-English, and Indian English as they are actually spoken. With code-switching handled naturally, not as an afterthought.</p>\n<p>The result? Your customer feels like they're talking to someone who gets them. Not a robot reading from a translated sheet.</p>\n<h2>What This Actually Means for Your Business</h2>\n<p><strong>What does 'understanding Indian languages' actually mean for your business?</strong></p>\n<p>It means your Tamil-speaking customer in Coimbatore doesn't have to switch to broken English to ask about their order.</p>\n<p>It means your Kannada-speaking patient in Bengaluru can explain symptoms the way they actually talk — mixing English medical terms with Kannada descriptions — and be understood.</p>\n<p>It means your Hindi-speaking insurance policyholder in Lucknow can ask 'Mera claim kitne din mein aa jayega?' and get a clear answer in the same language mix they used.</p>\n<p><strong>This isn't about checking a 'multilingual' box on a feature list.</strong> It's about the 250 million Indians who code-switch daily — who think in one language, count in another, and express emotions in a third. A voice platform that doesn't get that isn't built for India. It's built for a PowerPoint.</p>\n<h2>A Real Example</h2>\n<p>A major D2C brand launched in Tamil Nadu. Their voice support was 'English with Tamil option.'</p>\n<p>Result? 68% of Tamil-speaking customers abandoned calls within 60 seconds. They couldn't navigate the English menus. The 'Tamil' option was formal, textbook Tamil — not the Tanglish their customers actually spoke.</p>\n<p>After switching to a platform that understands real Tanglish:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Call abandonment dropped from 68% to 12%</li>\n<li>Average call duration increased (customers stayed to complete their query)</li>\n<li>CSAT scores for Tamil calls went from 2.8/5 to 4.3/5</li>\n</ul>\n<p>One customer actually said: 'Finally, someone who speaks like me.'</p>\n<p>That 'someone' was an AI. But the customer didn't care. They just wanted to be understood.</p>\n<h2>The Bigger Picture</h2>\n<p><strong>Why we built this:</strong> We watched our own families struggle with businesses that never answered their phones. The pharmacy that put you on hold. The clinic that never called back. The insurance company that sent robocalls instead of real conversations.</p>\n<p>We didn't set out to build 'AI.' We set out to fix the phone call. Everything else followed.</p>\n<p><strong>Curious what an AI agent would sound like for your business?</strong></p>\n<p>Visit <a href=\"https://speaksy.in\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">speaksy.in</a> and try our live demo. Call the number on the website. Interrupt the agent. Speak in Hinglish. Ask something unexpected.</p>\n<p>That's the real test. And we're happy to take it.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>About the Author</h2>\n<p><strong>Ayush Kulkarni</strong> — Co-founder &amp; Operations at Speaksy</p>\n<p>Ayush handles operations and makes sure Speaksy actually works for businesses that don't have an IT department. He's spoken to 800+ business owners who just wanted their phones answered.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Speaksy — AI voice agents that talk to India the way India actually talks.</em></p>\n<p><em>🇮🇳 Hinglish · Tanglish · Tenglish · Kanglish · Marathi-English · Indian English</em></p>\n<p><em>🌐 <a href=\"https://speaksy.in\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">speaksy.in</a> · 📞 AI voice agents for Indian businesses</em></p>"
